Log into your elk-server (192.168.56.30) and execute the following sequence.

1. The Kernel Tune-Up (Mandatory)
Elasticsearch will fail to start if the virtual memory limits are too low.

sudo sysctl -w vm.max_map_count=262144
echo "vm.max_map_count=262144" | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.conf


2. Run the Installation Script

cd ~/scripts/elk
sudo ./install_elk.sh


Fantastic. The stage is set, the Kubernetes cluster is healthy, and the path to the ELK node is clear.

🐘 Phase 2: ELK Stack Deployment
Log into your elk-server (192.168.56.30) and execute the following sequence.

1. The Kernel Tune-Up (Mandatory)
Elasticsearch will fail to start if the virtual memory limits are too low.

Bash
sudo sysctl -w vm.max_map_count=262144
echo "vm.max_map_count=262144" | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.conf
2. Run the Installation Script
Bash
cd ~/scripts/elk
sudo ./install_elk.sh
🛑 CRITICAL: Watch the Terminal Output!
Since you are likely installing Elasticsearch 8.x, the installer will generate security credentials only once at the very end of the apt-get install process.

DO NOT CLEAR YOUR SCREEN. Look for a block of text that looks like this:

✅ Elasticsearch security features have been automatically configured!
✅ Authentication is enabled and cluster connections are encrypted.

ℹ️  Password for the elastic user: xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx 👈 SAVE THIS!
ℹ️  HTTP CA certificate SHA256 fingerprint: ab12...cd34 👈 SAVE THIS!